APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF THE LIQUID WAS RELEASED DUE TO THE 55-GALLON DRUM BEING PUNCTURED BY A FORK LIFT. CF PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND PICKED UP THE SPILLED LIQUID WITH FLOOR DRY.

RELEASE WAS NOTED UPON OFFLOADING OF A TRANSPORT UNIT.  THE DOCK PERSONNEL WERE UNABLE TO ASCERTAIN WHAT MAY HAVE CAUSED THE FAILURE TO THE CONTAINER. THE FREE LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED UTILIZING BAKING SODA AND CONTAINERIZED FOR ULTIMATE DISPOSAL.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN UNLOADING TRL#9469 WE FOUND A 55 GAL DRUM OF MALATHION WAS LEAKING. WE EVACUATED THE TRAILER OF TWO PEOPLE THAT WAS BREAKING THE TRAILER FOR 45 MINS TO LET THE TRAILER AIR OUT.  WE CLEANSED UP THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH OIL DRY DESOPING IT CORRECTLY.

column42: TARS, LIQUID INCLUDING ROAD OILS AND CUTBACK BITUMENS
column168: AFTER LOADING, DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAKAGE.  TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE DOCK AND ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED ON ITS SIDE AND LEAKING.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: MAGNESIUM OR MAGNESIUM ALLOYS WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT MAGNESIUM IN PELLETS, TURNINGS OR RIBBONS
column168: UNLOADED FULL TRAILER OF GAYLORDS FULL OF METAL SHAVINGS.  SOME OF THE METAL SHAVINGS EITHER BOUNCED OR LEAKED OUT OF THE GAYLORDS ONTO THE FLOOR. SPILLED MATERIALS WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: TWO BAGS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE SEAMS.  THE SEAMS WERE RESEALED AND THE BAGS WERE FORWARDED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED RECOVERY DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WEARING PROPER P.P.E. RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE CRATES JUST OUTSIDE DOOR #57 ON THE RED BELT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX.  1 OF 4 ( 1 GALLON ) PLASTIC JUGS HAD A LOOSE CAP.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET THE CARTON AND LEAKING CONTAINER WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROCEDURES.  3 NON-CONTAMINATED ( 1 GALLON ) PLASTIC JUGS WERE REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER USING THE SALVAGE DRUM PROCEDURE.  DECONTAMINATED P.P.E.

LIQUID TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS DOING WALK AROUND OF THE TANK AND NOTICE SLIGHT DRIP BETWEEN INTERNAL VALVE AND THE QRB VALVE.  DRIVER PUTS A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP.  AFTER LOOKING AT THE DRIP CLOSER NOTICE CRACK IN OUTLET LEG. LIQUID TRANSPORT GETS ANOTHER CLEAN TRAILER OUT TO THE SCENE AND TRANSFER INTO THE CLEAN TRAILER.  THE TRANSFER WAS SUCCESSFUL.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: USED PROPER PPE.  CONTAINED AND ABSORBED LIQUID.  DISINFECTED AREA WITH BLEACH/WATER.  CLEAN AREA AND DISPOSED OF CONTAMINANTS IN A BIOHAZARD BOX.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER AT SOUTH CENTER BOXLINE.  WEARING PPE, IN DISCOVERED A FIVE-PART CORROSIVE HAZ-MAT THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF CLEAR LIQUID.  CONSULTED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET AND CONTAINED THE MATERIAL IN A SPILL TUB, AND REMOVED IT TO THE HAZ-MAT / REWRAP AREA.  INSPECTION SHOWED 1 OF 2 PLASTIC BOTTLES LEAKED DUE TO LOOSE CAP.  WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM AND SALVAGEABLE PORTION WAS REPACKAGED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RTS.

DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER, ASSOCIATE WAS ATTEMPTING TO MOVE DRUM WITH DRUM-TRUCK AND DRUM UNLATCHED FROM TRUCK AND WAS PUNCTURED ON SIDE BY FEET OF TRUCK.  SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 1 LB. OF PRODUCT.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO IMMEDIATE AREA.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: WHEN UNLOADING THE TRAILER OUT OF ORLANDO, FL WE FOUND THIS CARTON MASHED ON TOP.  THE CARTON WAS HELD HERE.
FORKLIFT PUNCTURED DRUM DURING MOVEMENT OF DRUM

ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF EPICHLOROHYDRIN WAS BEING UNLOADED ONTO A DOCK WHEN IT WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  SOME OF THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE DOCK AREA WHILE THE REST REMAINED ON THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE DOCK AREA AND ALL PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED FROM THE AREA.  ONCE THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS LEAKED OUT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE DOCK AREA, ASPHALT, AND TRAILER WAS CLEANED BY A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR.

TRAILER LOADED & ON SCALE PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE SHIPPER FACILITY. PRODUCT STARTED TO DRIP FROM THE TRAILER BELLY SKIN. PRODUCT PUMPED BACK INTO STORAGE WITH DRIPPING CONTAINED IN A BUCKET. TRAILER CLEANED & WILL BE SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS.

AFTER LOADING AT HARCROS CHEMICAL INC, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO BUCKMAN LABORATORIES, WHEN HE PULLED UP TO THE PLANT GATE AT BUCKMAN SPILLAGE OCCURRED FROM THE OVERFLOW TUBE ON COMPARTMENT #3.  UPON INVESTIGATING IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DOME LID HAD NEVER BEEN SECURED AFTER LOADING AT HARCROS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: WHILE PUMPING PROPANE INTO TANK FROM THE TRUCK, THE HOSE BEGAN TO LEAK. ESTIMATE 75 GALLON  RELEASED INTO THE AIR AND DISPENSED. CUSTOMER JIMMY MALLETT WAS NEAR THE HOSE AND WAS SPRAYED WITH PROPANE. HE SUFFERED FREEZE BURNS TO HIS LEFT FOOT LEFT RIB CAGE AREA LEFT CHEEK AND EYE LID. HE WENT TO THE DOCTOR FOR TREATMENT THE FOLLOWING DAY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE ARKANSAS OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES REPORT #1776
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRAILER IN PROCESS OF BEING LOADED WHEN PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING THEN TRAILER BELLY SKIN. RELEASES CONTAINED WITH A BUCKET & PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY. LEAKING TRAILER CLEANED & SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION & REPAIRS.

RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK AND MISSING AIR VALVE CLOSURE PLUG, RTMX 2663, MARCH 6, 2001 DETROIT DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, TUESDAY, MARCH 6, 2001, AT LINCOLN YARD IN DETROIT, MICHIGAN, FRA INSPECTOR NOTED PRODUCT VAPORS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RTMX 2663 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. DURING HIS INSPECTION HE DETERMINED THERE WAS A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK AND A MISSING AIR VALVE PLUG. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. ON MARCH 7,20001, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM RESCAR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND CHANGED THE 165 LB. RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK AND REPLACED THE MISSING AIR VALVE CLOSURE PLUG. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED FOR MOVEMENT. CODE 271 NARRI = 5(5+5+0) x (2+0)=100
DRIVER OVERFILLED 3000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND TANK RESULTING IN 20 GALLON DIESEL SPILL.  SPILL CLEANED BY DRIVER AND PLANT SHOP PERSONNEL.

TTI, COMMON CARRIER, PERFORMING WAREHOUSE TRANSFER BETWEEN OKC & TULSA BRANCHES.  TRAVELING EAST IN I-40.  DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF TRAILER.  DRIVER EXITED HARVEY STREET & PULLED INTO A VACANT LOT.  DRIVER NOTIFIED TTI AND THEY NOTIFIED PIONEER.  PIONEER OPERATIONS MANAGER ON SCENE AT 4:15PM & FIRE DEPARTMENT SHORTLY THEREAFTER.  FIRE DEPARTMENT BLOCKED OFF IMMEDIATELY AREA, DIKED DRAIN IN VACANT LOT, & BLOCKED OFF BOTH DIRECTIONS ON I-40.  OUR OPERATIONS MANAGER CONTACT ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANY  WHICH CLEANED UP FREEWAY & PARKING LOT.  MOST OF PRODUCT THAT LEAKED, LEAKED ON VACANT LOT.  MOST OF FREEWAY OPENED BACK UP BETWEEN 8 & 9PM, CLEANUP COMPLETE AT APPROXIMATELY 5AM, 3/2/01, WHEN TRAILER OPENED PRODUCT SEEMED TO BE IN ORDER (NOTICE TUNNED OVER OR IN DISARAY) TOTE WAS SPLIT ON REAR.  THERE DIDN'T APPEAR TO BE A PUNCTURE.  TOTE JUST SPLIT.

55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A HAND PALLETJACK THAT BROKE LOOSE FROM ITS RESTRAINTS (LORDBAR) DURING TRANSIT.  DRUM WAS INVERTED AND SECURED AT TIME OF DISCOVERY.  SPILL CONTAINED WITH ABSORBANT.  UNIT RETURNED TO TERMINAL WHERE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED THE GASOLINE STATION HE SPOTTED HIS VEHICLE ACCORDING TO INSTRUCTIONS CONTAINED ON EXXON/MOBIL ROUTE GUIDE FOR THAT STATION.  THE UNLEADED TANK REQUIRES A REMOTE FILL ARRANGEMENT TO UNLOAD WITH THE REMOTE FILL PIPE LOCATED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANKER WHILE THE ACTUAL UNDERGROUND GASOLINE STORAGE TANK IS ON THE LEFT SIDE OF HIS TRAILER (TANKER).  THE STICK READING FOR THE UNLEADED TANK MUST BE TAKEN DIRECTLY ABOVE THE TANK THROUGH WHAT IN ORDINARY INSTANCES WOULD BE THE USUAL FILL PIPE.  WHEN THE DRIVER TOOK THE BEGINNING STICK READING HE FAILED TO REPLACE THE CAP ON TOP OF THE FILL PIPE.  LATER WHEN HE STARTED FILLING/UNLOADING THE UNLEADED GASOLINE SOME OF THE GAS FOLLOWED THE PATH OF LEAST RESISTENCE AND CAME OUT THROUGH THE OPEN FILL PIPE.  THERE WAS NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  CLEANUP WAS INITIALLY DONE BY NORFOLK, VA FIRE DEPARTMENT AND OIL TRANSPORT HM RESPONSE TEAM.  THE ENTIRE AREA WAS AGAIN FLUSHED AND CLEANED UP BY A COMMERCIAL CONTRACTOR.  WE HAVE REVISED AND EMPHASIZED OUR UNLOADING INSTRUCTIONS FOR WARDS CORNER EXXON AND OTHER STATIONS USING REMOTE FILLS.

column168: A FORK BLADE ACCIDENTLY INSERTED BETWEEN TOP OF SKID AND BOTTOM OF CARTON PUNCTURED VERY BOTTOM OF CARTON AND 2 CANS ON LEFT SIDE CAUSING SMALL HOLE IN 2 CANS VERY LITTLE MATERIAL LEAKED OUT.  RETRAIN IN THE USE OF THE TOWMOTOR AND MOVING OF FREIGHT, ESPECIALLY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

THE CONSIGNEE FINISHED UNLOADING THE REST OF THE PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER, AND TOOK THE OVERPACK DRUM TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO GET IT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  OUR DRIVER WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO HIS NEXT PICK-UP.

APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 HOURS, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM SUN AND UNION TANK CAR COMPANY ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A CUT MANWAY COVER GASKET. column42: CHLOROSILANES, N.O.S., WHICH IN CONTACT WITH WATER EMIT FLAMMABLE GASES
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30PM, 03-13-01, MASTER MECHANIC, STEVE WILKINS, WAS NOTIFIED THAT GATX 73723 WAS LEAKING,  AFTER RUNNING ALL HAZ-MAT REQUIREMENTS, MASTER MECHANIC PROCEEDED TO MANCHESTER YARD.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP, WAS SECURED FROM LEAKING AND MOVE TO SAFETY-KLEEN FOR UNLOADING.
THREE BAGS WERE LOCATED TORN/PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADES.  THE DAMAGED BAGS & RELEASED PRODUCT WERE RECOUPED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

TWO BAGS WERE LOCATED DAMAGED.  ONE BAG WAS TORN ON CORNER OF PALLET WHEN BAGS SHIFTED ON SKID OVERLAPPING THE SIDES OF THE PALLET.  THE SECOND BAG WAS LOCATED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE SKID TOWARD THE TIP - IT APPEARS IT HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY TORN PRIOR TO LOADING.  THE DAMAGED BAGS / RELEASED PRODUCT WERE OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR.

TWO BAGS WERE LOCATED LEAKING ON THE SHIPMENT.  ONE BAG WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADE ( OPERATOR WAS RE-EDUCATED FOR PROPER USE OF DOCK EQUIPMENT).  THE SECOND BAG WAS LOCATED AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A SEAM THAT WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  THE RELEASED WAS REMEDIATED BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR.  BOTH DAMAGED BAGS & RELEASED PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.
FIVE BAGS WERE LOCATED PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADES.  THE DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  THE CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR.
ADJACENT FREIGHT WAS PUSHED INTO ONE SKID TEARING ONE BAG OF PRODUCT.  THE DAMAGED BAG & PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM; THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR.
TWO BAGS WERE FOUND LEAKING: ONE WITH TAPE ON THE SIDE & ONE BAG WITH A FAILED SEAM. THE DAMAGED BAGS & RELEASED PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR.

ONE BAG WAS FOUND LEAKING; THE CAUSE IS ATTRIBUTED TO FAILED SEAL/SEAM ON END OF THE BAG. THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR; THE LEAKING BAG & SPILLED PRODUCT WERE RECOUPED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

FREIGHT WAS BAYED AT THE CENTER; APPARENTLY WHILE SITTING AWAITING MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION THE BAG WAS RIPPED BY PASSING FREIGHT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY A CONTRACTOR; ALL DAMAGED CONTAINERS & SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE PRODUCT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FUEL TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT SMOKEY CANYON MINE WHEN A FILLING HOSE FITTING VIBRATED LOOSE AND FUEL BEGAN TO SPILL. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP OFF. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF FUEL SPILLED. THE MINING PERSONNEL REMOVED THE EFFECTED SOIL AND DEPOSITED IT TO THE APPROVED LAND FARM ON SITE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE HYDOPLANED ON WET ROADS, LEFT HIGHWAY OVERTURING ON RIGHT SIDE. DRIVER WAS UNCONSCIOUS FOR UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF TIME.  EMERGENCY CALLS WENT OUT AT 0530.  DURING THIS TIME THE VAPOR VENTS ON TOP OF TRAILER WERE STUCK OPEN BY MUD.  (APPROX. 1 HOUR) .  SINCE THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED, WE HAVE HAD SAFETY MEETINGS AT ALL TERMINALS WITH ALL DRIVERS TO DISCUSS THIS ACCIDENT AND WHAT ACTIONS COULD POSSIBLY HAVE PREVENTED THE ROLL OVER. SOLUTIONS IN PLACE TO PREVENT POSSIBLE RE-OCCURANCE ARE TRAINING PROGRAMS (INCLUDING VIDEOS COVERING WET WEATHER DRIVING AND ROLL OVER PREVENTION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON A RAINY DAY, A PASSENGER CAR PULLED OUT AHEAD OF OUR DELIVERY TRUCK. OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID HITTING THE CAR, CAUSING THE TRUCK TO GO OUT OF CONTROL AND EVENTUALLY ROLL ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO SLIDE INTO AN ONCOMING SEWAGE TRUCK.  THE COLLISION SHEARED THE FILL VALVE AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THE TRUCK THEN CAME TO A REST AT THE SIDE OF THE ROAD IN A DITCH.  AFTER DISCOVERING THE ACCIDENT, WE RESPONDED AND SECURED THE TANK AND FLARED OFF PRODUCT TO KEEP VESSEL PRESSURE LOW.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED, IF THE ADJOINING ROAD WHERE THE INCIDENT STARTED INTERSECTED THE MAIN ROAD AT A RIGHT ANGLE ALLOWING THE PASSENGER CAR TO SEE THE ONCOMING TRAFFIC WITHOUT LOOKING REARWARD.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE RAN OFF ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED.  DRIVER TRANSPORTED TO HOSPITAL WITH BROKEN ANKLE AND VARIOUS MINOR BRUISED.  DRIVER WAS ADMITTED FOR TREATMENT AND OBSERVATION.  TEXAS DPS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGY GROUP, INC FROM MIDLAND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND PROVIDES CLEAN UP PER TEXAS TNRCC.

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: HAD A TANK FILL UP AND PRODUCT RAN OUT OF THE TANK.  DRIVER SHUT OFF VALVE. HAD A RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  FIRE DEPT., POLICE, COUNTY HAZMAT OFFICER, MCDANIEL REPRESENTATIVE, INSURANCE, AND ENVIRONMENTAL CREW, WERE ALL DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND SITE HAS BEEN RESTORED. DRIVER WILL CONTINUE TO GO THROUGH RETRAINING.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED TO UNLOAD AND WAS TOLD THAT STORAGE TANK WOULD NOT HOLD WHOLE LOAD AND SOME PRODUCT WAS TO BE UNLOADED INTO TOTE DRUMS.  PLANT PERSONNEL HELD HOSE IN DRUMS WHILE DRIVER OPERATED PUMP CONTROLS.  PLANT PERSONNEL ALLOWED THE HOSE TO COME OUT OF THE DRUM SPILLINGS ABOUT 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  CONSIGNEE HANDLED CLEAN UP.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: UTLX 46886 NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED.  CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES, HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED AND ATTEMPTED TO CONTROL THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  EFFORTS TO STOP THE LEAK WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND AN EMERGENCY MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WAS APPLIED FOR TO MOVE THE CAR APPROXIMATELY 3 MILES TO THE CONSIGNEES FACILITY FOR OFF-LOADING. FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FRA-0101052 WAS GRANTED AND THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT WITHOUT INCIDENT.  AFTER UNLOADING THE CAR IS TO BE CLEANED, INSPECTED AND REPAIRED.  3 CARRIER EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY FOR A PRECAUTIONARY EXAMINATION.  ALL WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.

THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED STOPPING THE ODOR RELEASE.

CAP ON DRUM WAS LOOSE FROM MFG.  CAP WAS TIGHTENED & MOVED ON FOR DELIVERY.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: RESPONDED TO THE UNLOAD DOOR #7 TRAILER #TIPZ 226533 TO A 4 FOOT SPILL WHICH INVOLVED 4 IRREGULAR PACKAGES OVER 70 LBS AND 4 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGES.  THE LEAKER, A CORROSIVE LIQUID PACKAGE WITH ORIENTATION ARROWS WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED THE SPILL.  1 OF 2 1-GALLON METAL PAINT STYLE CANS LEAKED FROM THE LID.  (THE CAN WAS UNDENTED AND HAD THE REQUIRED 6 CUPS.)  THE NON-CONTAMINATED GALLON CAN AND NON-CONTAMINATED CONTENTS OF THE OTHER 3 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGES WERE RE-PACKED AND RETURNED TO THEIR SHIPPERS IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  ALL CONTAMINATED CARTONS, LEAKING CONTAINER AND CONTAMINATED P.P.E. WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROCEDURES.
PIECE OF ANGLE IRON LOADED NEXT TO TOTE PUNCTURING TOTE NEAR TOP. TERMINAL ABLE TO PATCH TOTE FOR DELIVERY AND NEUTRALIZE SPILLED MATERIAL IN TRAILER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: ASHLAND WAS UNLOADING WASTE RESIN AT OUR TEMPORARY STORAGE TERMINAL IN DAYTON OH. SHIPMENT WAS FROM SILGAN CONTAINERS (INDIANA) TO RINECO CHEMICAL (ARKANSAS) FOR DISPOSAL. WHILE UNLOADING MATERIAL AT TERMINAL IN DAYTON, OH A SKID PUNCTURED 1 DRUM. DRUM WAS BANDED  ON SKID TO THREE OTHERS, SO ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE LOST BEFORE DRUM COULD BE ORIENTED TO STEP LEAK. MATERIALS CLEANED UP THAT WAS CONTAINED IN TRAILER USING ABSORBENTS.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL PPE I SALLIED TOWARDS A LEAKING PACKAGE UPON THE PRIMARY SORT AISLE. I INSPECTED THE LEAKING PACKAGE. I NOTED A WET STAIN, A DOT 5-PART LABEL, A CORROSIVE DOT DIAMOND LABEL. I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING ITS INDICATORS TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET. UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE RESPONSE SHEET. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE DMN PROCESS, THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. I ENDED BY DECONTAMINATING MY P.P.E.

I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. I FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE SHEET: THE SPILL WS ISOLATED, THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE DMN PROCESS, THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, MY PPE WAS DECONTAMINATED

column168: RELEASE WAS NOTED UPON OFFLOADING OF A TRANSPORT UNIT (TRAILER NUMBER 171510). THE SHIPMENT WAS A SPLIT BILL AND THIS PORTION INCLUDED 2 TANKS OUT OF 20 (PRO NUMBER537924634). DOCK PERSONNEL WERE UNABLE TO OBTAIN UN PERFORMANCE PACKAGING MARKINGS AND/OR SERIAL NUMBERS DUE TO EXCESSIVE PAINT BUILD UP FROM PRIOR UTILIZATION OF THE TOTE TANK IN QUESTION. THE DOCK PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO CONTROL THE RELEASE AND CLEANUP THE AREA OF CONTAMINATION. THE FREE LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED FOR ULTIMATE DISPOSAL.

THE FREIGHT HAD SHIFTED CAUSING 2-5 GALLON PAILS TO STRIKE AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT. THE PAILS WERE DAMAGED AROUND THE TOP RIM AND THE PRODUCT RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE PAILS, HARDENING QUICKLY AND NOT REACHING THE GROUND. THE PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A 15 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT WAS RELEASED. NO PERSONNEL WAS AFFECTED BY THE INCIDENT. THE INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY IMPROPER LOADING PROCEDURES. CARE AND PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES MUST BE FOLLOWED AT ALL TIMES.

column42: MERCAPTANS, LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. OR MERCAPTAN MIXTURE, LIQUID, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S.
column168: A 5-GALLON STEEL CONTAINER CARRYING MERCAPTAN WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING UPON OPENING OF THE TRAILER. THE CAN WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND MOVED TO AN AREA THAT ALLOWED IT TO AIR. THE MERCAPTAN SMELL IS VERY STRONG. THE CAN WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND OVERPACKED TO TRY TO STOP THE ODOR. NOTE: OTHER THAN RUST AROUND THE BOTTOM RIM THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF FAILURE. THE ODOR WAS NOT COMPLETELY CONTROLLED SO THE PROCESS WAS REPEATED BY WRAPPING THE 30-GALLON CONTAINER IN PLASTIC AND THIS OVERPACKING IT IN A 55-GALLON DRUM. THE ODOR PERSISTED SO AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED. THE RESPONSE TEAM REPACKED THE 5-GALLON CAN BUT THIS TIME USED CARBON POWDER AS PACKING TO ABSORB THE ODOR. THE OVERPACK WAS THEN SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.
column172: Metal can, capacity 7 gallons or less

column168: APPROXIMATELY 15-20 GALLONS OF THE LIQUID WAS RELEASED DUE TO THE 55-GALLON DRUM BEING PUNCTURED BY A FORK LIFT. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND PICKED UP THE SPILLED LIQUID WITH FLOOR DRY.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THIRD QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS AND GLOVES. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, ABSORBENTS, AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE FOR DISPOSAL. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SEVENTY GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS OF EXTRACT FLAVORING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 26 OF THE 268 CONTAINERS WERE SEEPING AROUND THE LIDS (PACKAGING FAILURE). AN ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR THEN CAME ON SITE AND CONSOLIDATED THE PRODUCT INTO THREE 55-GALLON DRUMS AND WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE SUBCONTRACTOR'S FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL. THE EMPTY 5-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE ALSO PACKAGED AND TAKEN TO THE SUBCONTRACTOR'S FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL.

UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS, CF PERSONNEL NOTICED A FINE POWDER ON THE FLOOR. THE BILL OF LADING INDICATED THAT THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS A TOXIC SUBSTANCE. CF CONTACTED E.M.I FOR ASSISTANCE TO THE INCIDENT. A REPUTABLE ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE REMEDIATION. ONCE ON SITE CACTUS ENVIRONMENTAL PLACED THE DAMAGED BAGS INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR TRANSPORT TO AN APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY. ALL INDICATIONS WERE THAT THE DAMAGE TO THE BAGS HAPPENED ENROUTE. THERE WAS NOT ANY PERSONNEL AFFECTED BY THE INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE WALKING BY TRAILER 191726, MR DAVE HEFFERNAN OF CONSOLIDATED FREIGHT WAYS (CF) NOTICED THAT THERE WERE SOME CRUSHED BOXES OF FREIGHT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS  A TOXIC SOLIDS NOS CONTAINING SODIUM FLUORIDE AND POTASSIUM OXALATE. ONCE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE ALL OF THE CRUSHED BOXES CONTAINING BROKEN VIALS WERE PLACED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS(S). THE CONSENSUS OF CF AND THE RESPONSE TEAM PERSONNEL WAS THAT EITHER THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED OR THE BOXES OF THE TOXIC SOLIDS HAD BEEN LOADED IMPROPERLY. THE BOXES WERE FOUND STACKED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WITH FREIGHT ON TOP. IMPROPER LOADING PROCEDURES WERE USED. THERE WERE NO PERSONNEL AFFECTED BY THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

CENTRAL'S PUMP WAS LEAKING.

DRIVER WAS TRAVELING THROUGH CONSTRUCTION ZONE WHEN MISHAP OCCURRED. DRIVER OF VEHICLE DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF OUR UNIT CAME TO IMMEDIATE HAULT FOR UNKNOWN REASONS. OUR UNIT WAS FORCE TO BRAKE HARD, AS A RESULT FREIGHT SHIFTED INTO DRUM CAUSING SPILL. ENTIRE DRUM WAS LOST IN PROCESS. SEFL PERSONNEL WAS DISPATCH TO SCENE TO ORGANIZE CLEAN UP. SPILL MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED AND PREPARED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: TRUCK WAS IN ROUTE FROM PRYOR, OR TO JACKSONVILLE, AR.  DRIVE HAD PERFORMED A VEHICLE SAFETY CHECK APPROX.  15 MILES PRIOR TO INCIDENT.  AT APPROX MILE MARKER 7 AFTER CROSSING INTO AR.  THE DRIVER HEARD A POP AND PULLED OVER TO INVESTIGATE.  RARE DOORS OF THE UNIT WERE FROSTING AND LIQUID WAS RUNNING FROM UNDER THE DOORS.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE E.R. TEAM IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE WAS OPEN 1/2 TURN ALLOWING LIQUID TO FLOW.  TRAILER WAS EMPTY AT THIS TIME.  UPON RETURNING UNIT TO VEHICLE SHOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE RETAINING SNAP RING SECURING THE VALVE GLOBE AND BUSING HAL BROKEN ALLOWING GLOBE TO FLOAT OFF SEAT ALLOWING LIQUID TO FLOW.  AR ANY PATROL HAD CLOSED I-40 EAST BOUND FOR SAFETY DUE TO VAPOR CLOUD FROM PRODUCT AND POSSIBILITY OF IT DRIFTING ACROSS THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED FOR 3 1/2 HOURS.

ON MARCH 2, 2001 CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES,INC. (CHESI) WAS TRANSFERRING INTERMODAL CONTAINERS, WHICH HAD INNER LINERS FROM CHESI TRANSPORTERS TO NORFOLK SOUTHERN RAILROAD CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID N.O.S. (BENZENE).  DURING THE TRANSFER PROCESS THE INTERMODALS WERE STAGED ON THE GROUND WAITING TO BE PLACED ON RAILCARS.  TWO OF THE CONTAINERS STARTED TO LEAK A LIQUID MATERIAL WHILE SITTING ON THE GROUND.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CHESI PERSONNEL INITIATED CLEAN UP OPERATIONS. ALL THE INTERMODALS THAT WERE STAGED WERE RE-LOADED BACK ONTO CHESI TRANSPORTERS AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO CHESI CINCINNATI FOR QC.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A BACK DOOR ON ONE OF THE INTERMODALS WAS NOT COMPLETELY TIGHTENED AND SNOW AND ICE WHICH WAS BETWEEN THE INNER LINER AND THE INTERMODAL LIQUIFIED AND LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINER.  CHESI PERSONNEL REMOVED ALL MATERIAL FROM ALL OF THE BACK DOORS AND RE-SEALED THE AREA.

column168: PASCHAL DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD AND DISCOVERED THAT HE HAD PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER. THE CONSIGNEE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND THE SHIPPER SENT ONYX CLEAN-UP CREW OUT TO DETERMINE WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS. IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW THAT A SCREW HAD WORKED IT'S WAY OUT OF THE BACK METAL PLATE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND LODGED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BARREL ON THE VERY BACK OF THE LOAD. THEREFORE THE SCREW ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE DRUM ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP. THE LOAD WAS THEN ACCEPTED AND OUR DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO HIS NEXT PICK-UP.

THE CAR LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE OF WHICH APPROXIMATELY 9 GALLONS WAS CONTAINED IN BUCKETS. THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. NARRI=300 CODE=242

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: THIS CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DUE TO THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE BEING LEFT LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE SHIPPER SENT OUT THE LOADERS OF THE CAR TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR WHICH WAS TO TIGHTEN THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE WRENCH TIGHT. THE CAR AND HE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE CAR CLEANED. AT THIS TIME THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO MOVE FORWARD. NARRI: 5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100 CAUSE CODE =249

THIS CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD AT MOBIL, AL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE EAST CLEAN OUT TRACK AND A CATCH PAN WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT DRIPPING OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER RETAINED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS. INVESTIGATION FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT ON THE EDUCATION LINE NIPPLE. THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED WRENCH TIGHT AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. APPROX. 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. NARRI:5(5+3+0)X2+0)=80 CAUSE CODE=282

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: UTLX 200307 TANK CAR OF METHANOL FOUND LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET IN SELKIRK YARD BY CAR INSPECTOR. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND LEAK WAS CONTAINED. CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER RESPONDED AND FOUND TWO SECUREMENT NUTS ON BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE, A-END, LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. BOTH NUTS WERE TIGHTENED ONE AND A HALF TURNS. LEAK WAS STOPPED. TANK CAR WAS HELD OVERNIGHT TO VERIFY LEAK HAD STOPPED. 03-16-01 0800 HRS. GENERAL ELECTRIC RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER TO INSPECT TANK CAR. GORETEX WAS APPLIED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE GASKET AS A PRECAUTION BEFORE TRANSPORTATION OF THE TANK CAR. GENERAL ELECTRIC REQUESTED THE TANK CAR BE DIVERTED TO THEIR PLANT AT SELKIRK, NY. UTLX200307 WAS DELIVERED TO NEW DESTINATION AT 1430 HRS.

GATX 22296 TANK CAR SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION FOUND LEAKING BY CAR INSPECTOR. PRODUCT LEAKING OVER B-END TRUCK ASSEMBLY. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND LEAK CONTAINED. OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CONTRACTED SEVENSON ENVIRONMENTAL TO TRANSFER LADING INTO GATX 90707. SUCCESSFUL TRANSFER COMPLETED 1600 HRS AND TANK CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED. FRA GRANTED MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FRA 0103054 TO RETURN TANK CAR HOME FOR REPAIRS.

UPON ARRIVING AT THE OAKWORTH YARD IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 94901 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. THE SHIPPER OF THE CAR WAS CALLED AND MADE AWARE OF THE SITUATION. THE SHIPPER SENT A TEAM OF PERSONNEL TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR. UPON INSPECTING THE CAR THE SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE GASKET ON THE LIQUID LOADING LINE WAS DEFECTIVE AND HAD ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. THE INTERNAL PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS RELIEVED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED ON THE LIQUID LOADING LINE VALVE. THE SHIPPER NORMALLY PUTS A BLANKET OF 15 PSI IN THE CAR. THIS ADDITIONAL PRESSURE APPEARED TO INCREASE THE SEVERITY OF THE RELEASES. THE SHIPPER'S TEAM CLEANED THE EXTERIOR SURFACE OF THE CAR AND THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO EXCAVATE AND REMOVE SOIL, BALLAST, AND RAIL TIES EXPOSED (IMPACTED) BY THE SPILLED MATERIALS. NARRI: 150=5(5+5+0)X(3+0) CODE=286

UNLOADING TRAILER, FOUND ONE CARTON WITH ONE 1/2 GALLON CAN LEAKING. SPILL PROPERLY CLEANED UP.

WHILE UNLOADING PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THAT A ONE GALLON CONTAINER OF PHOSPHORIC ACID HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS ONE GALLON. RELEASE IMPACTED 2 PALLETS OF CARDBOARD. A RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO REMOVE ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE RESPONSE TEAM'S TERMINAL PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

A 5 GAL PAIL WAS FOUND LEAKING INSIDE THE TRAILER CAUSING A SMALL LEAK DUE TO FAILURE OF THE LID TO SEAL TO THE DRUM. THIS IS WHAT WAS DETERMINED BY CF PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A 30 GAL OVERPACK AND WILL AWAIT PICKUP FOR DISPOSAL BY AN EMI SUBCONTRACTOR.
FIVE GALLON PAIL DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT.ONLY ONE OUNCE OF PRODUCT LOST FROM THE CONTAINER. THE PAIL WAS OVERPACKED INTO A TEN GALLON CONTAINER AND SHIPPED ON TO CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT USING A FORKLIFT, A PUNCTURE WAS MISTAKENLY PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM. CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS (CF) PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND ABSORBED ALL FREE PRODUCT. NO CF PERSONNEL WAS AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE. CARE MUST ALWAYS BE TAKEN WHEN USING A FORKLIFT TO UNLOAD FREIGHT.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT USING A FORKLIFT, A 5 GALLON POLY PAIL WAS PUNCTURED. CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS (CF) PERSONNEL PLACED THE PAIL INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM. ALL FREE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED. WHEN UTILIZING A FORKLIFT FOR REMOVAL OF FREIGHT CARE MUST ALWAYS BE TAKEN SO AS NOT TO DAMAGE FREIGHT OR INJURE PERSONNEL.

column168: AT 7:45 AM, OUTSIDE OPERATOR ATTACHED STEAM TO RAILCAR AT THE UNLOAD STATION. AFTER 30-45 MINUTES, A LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM REAR SECTION OF THE CAR. AND WATER WAS APPLIED TO COOL CAR DOWN, SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS DIKED AROUND THE SPILL TO CONTAIN IT. (SULFUR AND ACID WATER RUN OFF). WHEN CAR WAS FULLY FROZEN, IT WAS MOVED FOR CLEANUP. column168: ON FEBRUARY 27,2001, THE DRIVER FOR BURLINGTON MOTOR CARRIERS WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL ON AN EXIT RAMP DURING A SNOWSTORM AND JACKKNIFED HIS UNIT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE LOAD AND FOUND NO LEAKS. BY THE TIME THE DRIVER REACHED THE CONSIGNEE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED. IT IS OUR OPINION THE SHRINK WRAP BECAME LOOSE IN THE ACCIDENT AND EVENTUALLY GAVE WAY ALLOWING THE DRUMS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE ( SWIMMING POOL CHLORINE) TO FALL. THE LOAD WAS REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND WE CONTRACTED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIALS AND RESTACK THE LOAD. NO PRODUCT ESCAPED THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 20 PLASTIC BUCKETS OF MATERIALS HAD BEEN DAMAGED. A TOTAL OF EIGHT DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THIS INCLUDED THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS AND PRODUCT.

column168: THE CARGO TANK INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT HAD BEEN LOANED OUT AS A REMOTE TANK FOR A CONSTRUCTION COMPANY AND HAD BEEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 YEARS.  THE TANK WAS INSPECTED UNDER THE ANNUAL INSPECTION PROGRAM ON 02-27-01 AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.  UNKNOWN TO THE INSPECTOR, AND TO THE DRIVER DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION, 2 OF THE 4 VAPOR RECOVERY VENTS ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER HAD BEEN BLOCKED OPEN WITH STRIPS OF WOOD. AS THE VEHICLE STARTED UP A STEEP HILL, THE USED MOTOR OIL CARRIER SURGED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND ESCAPED THROUGH THE BLOCKED OPEN VAPOR RECOVERY VENTS.  THIS CARGO TANK WAS REMOVED FROM SPECIFICATION SERVICE IN 1996.  THE COMPANY WILL NOW REQUIRE THAT ALL TANKS, EVEN NON-SPECIFICATION TANKS WILL BE INSPECTED BY A CERTIFIED CARGO TANK COMPANY PRIOR TO USE IF THE TANK HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM SERVICE BY THE COMPANY.

column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION THE BOX TIPPED OVER CAUSING ONE CONTAINER TO LEAK.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE BOX, AND WE PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND IT IS BEING HELD AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
DURING TRANSPORTATION THE CAP CAME LOOSE ON ONE CONTAINER CAUSING SOME MINIMAL SEEPAGE.  THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED THE SHIPMENT WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DURING THE COURSE OF OFF LOADING THE RESIN, ONE OF THE CUSTOMERS LINES RUPTURED DUE TO A VALVE IN THE LINE NOT BEING OPENED ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPRAY OUT ONTO THE TRACTOR, TRAILER, AND SOME ON THE DRIVER.  CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY THE CUSTOMER.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR CLEAN UP AND CHECK UP NO NOTED INJURIES OR REQUIRED TREATMENT.  ASSURANCE THAT ALL VALVES ARE OPEN AND READY TO RECEIVE LOAD WILL BE MADE ON ALL FUTURE SHIPMENTS TO THIS FACILITY.

column168: WE WERE ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMERS STORAGE FACILITY.  THE LINE WE WERE DIRECTED TO HOOK-UPTO HADN'T BEEN USED IN TWO YEARS.  WE HOOKED-UP  AND STARTED TO UNLOAD WHEN THE CUSTOMERS LINE SPLIT AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 30-40 GALLONS OF HOT ASPHALT.  EXAMINATION OF LINE SHOWED THAT LINE HAD RUSTED THROUGH FROM THE INSIDE OUT AND PLANT ACKNOWLEDGED THAT INCIDENT WAS THEIR RESPONSIBILITY.  PLANT PERSONNEL CONTAINED MATERIAL WITH SAND AND THEN CLEANED UP ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE PLANT MANAGER JOHN WINTBAUER CONDUCTED AN INVESTIGATION WHICH VERIFIED THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE.  AN EMPLOYEE OF JESCO GOT SOME OF THE PRODUCT IN HER HAIR, BUT WAS NOT BURNED OR OTHERWISE INJURIES.

column168: TRUCK WAS IN ROUTE FOR DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO SERVICE STATION IN ALTAMONT TENNESSEE.  THE TRUCK WENT WIDE IN A CURVE AND WENT OVER AN EMBANKMENT. TWO HAZ-MAT TEAMS WERE DISPATCHED, THE REMAINDER OF THE CARGO UNLOADED, AND CLEANUP OF SPILLED GALLONS COMMENCED.  THERE HAVE BEEN NUMEROUS ACCIDENTS OF THE SAME NATURE IN THIS CURVE AND I HIGHLY RECOMMEND A GUARD RAIL BE INSTALLED.
HOSE DEVELOPED SMALL HOLE WHICH CAUSED AN OUTAGE WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, THREE QUARTERS OF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY, THE LEAK TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUM, WAS PLACED INTO A SIXTY FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND IS AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING FIVE GALLON STEEL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT WHICH CAUSED THE LIDS TO POP OFF THE PAILS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, BOTTIES AND OIL-DRY.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LIDS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE LEAKING PAILS AND THE PAILS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, EIGHT GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUMS.  THE OVERPACK DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE ON THE DOCK, THREE WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING SIX, ONE HALF GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED. column168: TRANSPORT DRIVER APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP WHILE IN ROUTE TO DELIVER GASOLINE. VEHICLE WENT OFF RIGHT SIDE OF ROADWAY TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 1500 YARDS DOWN BERM AND ROAD SIDE. CARGO TANK ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, PUSHING TRACTOR BROADSIDE THROUGH A GROVE OF TREES. THE TREES RIPPED THE VAPOR RECOVERY AND INSPECTION DOMES OFF THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK, AS IT SLID ALONG. THE GASOLINE SPILLED OUT FROM THE OPEN HOLES UNTIL EQUALIZING AT THE HOLES LOWEST POINT. ALL SAFETY AND ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS WERE ALERTED AND RESPONDED. AREA WAS SECURED AND HAZARD WAS CLEANED UP. OWNER HAS RESPONDED WITH SAFETY MEETINGS AND PRECAUTIONS ON "NIGHT" DRIVING AND DRIVER FATIGUE" TRAINING.

column168: ON 03/23/01 ANSETT AIR FREIGHT SHIPPED A CONSOLIDATION SHIPMENT CONTAINING TWO HOUSES BILLS ON FLIGHT UA848 FROM MEL TO LAX.  SHIPMENT WAS LISTED AS AIRCRAFT PARTS AND NOT DECLARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  AT APPROX 2300 ON 03/28/01 RUSSO TRUCKING ARRIVED TO PICK UP HOUSE BILL NUMBER VEA120602. WHEN THE BOX WAS PLACED ON THE TRUCK THE DRIVER TURNED IT ON ITS SIDE TO INSPECT THE FRIGHT AND THE BOX STARTED LEAKING A FUEL LIKE SUBSTANCE.  THE DRIVER CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR AND WAS ADVISED TO REFUSE IT.  THE UAL AGENT AT THE FRONT DOOR THEN CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR JEFF ARNOLD WHO REMOVED THE BOX TO A SECURE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  SUBSEQUENTLY SUPERVISOR ARNOLD OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND WARRANTY REPAIR FORM LISTING @2 ENGINE MAIN FUEL CONTROL LEAKING ADJACENT TO PLA INPUT SHAFT"  BOX IS 22KG CARDBOARD WITH STYROFOAM PEANUTS.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING ON THE DAN RYAN EXPRESSWAY (I-94) ENROUTE TO THE GARDNER ASPHALT FACILITY IN CHICAGO. THE DRIVER WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY A MOTORIST WHO HAD INDICATED THE TANKER WAS LEAKING. THE DRIVER PROMPTLY PULLED THE VEHICLE ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND INSPECTED THE TANKER. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ASPHALT WAS DRIZZLING ASPHALT FROM THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE INSULATION OF THE CARGO TANK. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE EMERGENCY SERVICES WHERE THE HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TOE THE SCENE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED BY CONTAINING THE MATERIAL SEEPING FROM THE TANKER WITH SAND AND ATTEMPTED TO COOL IT USING WATER. OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HMHTTC, INC. WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE WITH EQUIPMENT TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN-UP THE LEAKING ASPHALT. DUE TO SPACIAL CONSTRAINTS AND SAFETY CONCERNS THE HIGHWAY PATROL CLOSED DOWN THE  NORTHBOUND LANES OF THE EXPRESSWAY TO ALLOW UNRESTRICTED ACCESS TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE  PERSONNEL. THE LEAKING TANKER WAS OFF LOADED INTO AN APPROVED TANKER USING AN ONBOARD P.T.O. PUMP AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE GARDNER FACILITY WHERE IT WAS OFF LOADED. THE LEAKING TANKER WAS WRAPPED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING, TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL DRIPPING, AND TRANSPORTED TO THE GARDNER FACILITY. THE TANKER WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TRANSPORTED TO JACOB PRESS & SONS, INC. LOCATED AT 9001 W. 79TH PLACE,  JUSTICE, IL FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. THE INSPECTION FACILITY DETERMINED THAT THE CARGO TANK REPAIR COST WOULD BE EXCESSIVE AND IT WAS DECOMMISSIONED AND WILL BE SCRAPED. HMHTTC SCRAPED THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT AND CONTAINERIZED THE SAND AND ASPHALT IN A LINED WASTE DUMPSTER. THE DUMPSTER WAS TRANSFERRED TO HMHTTC'S CALUMET CITY YARD WHERE IT AWAITS WASTE ACCEPTANCE AT THE LOCAL NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE LANDFILL.

THIS SPILL OCCURRED ON ONE OF THE FEDEX DELIVERY VEHICLES WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS MAKING DELIVERIES IN MINNEAPOLIS. THE DRIVER NOTICED A STRONG SOLVENT ODOR AND STOPPED THE VEHICLE. UPON FREIGHT INSPECTION , HE FOUND THIS PACKAGE OF UN1993 LEAKING. THE LOCAL STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST WAS NOTIFIED AND CAME TO THE VEHICLE TO CLEANUP THE SPILL. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICY. NONE OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF THE VAN, SO FEDEX ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOT NOTIFIED. BECAUSE OF THE STRONG SOLVENT ODOR, THE VAN WAS TOWED BACK TO THE FEDEX MICA STATION AFTER THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON ANOTHER DELIVERY VEHICLE. THERE IS CURRENTLY NO LIQUID OR ODOR ON THIS DELIVERY VEHICLE, SO IT IS BACK IN SERVICE. THE COURIER SUFFERED NO PHYSICAL PROBLEMS BECAUSE OF THIS SPILL. THIS PACKAGE IS BEING HELD FOR PICKUP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL DISPOSAL COMPANY PER THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST FOR DISPOSAL. THE PACKAGE THAT DID NOT LEAK WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

TRAILER WAS EMPTIED OF FREIGHT AND THE LEAKING DRUM RECOVERED AND OVERPACKED.  THE TRAILER FLOOR AND GROUND WERE CLEANED.  TWO DRUMS OF PRODUCT AND DEBRIS ARE AWAITING DISPOSAL AT THE TERMINAL.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON ROUTE 1 IN BRUNSWICK, MAINE AT APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH THE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD NOISE COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER PULLED THE TRUCK OVER INTO THE BREAKDOWN LANE IMMEDIATELY AND FOUND PRODUCT SPILLING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO KEEP THE SPILL CONTAINED WITH SORBENT PADS AND THEN CALLED THE DISPATCHER ON THE COMPANY RADIO FOR HELP.  ON CLOSER INSPECTION THE DRIVER FOUND THE DRIVE SHAFT HAD BECOME DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRANSMISSION DUE TO FAILURE OF A UNIVERSAL JOINT.  THE END OF THE DRIVESHAFT HAD BOUNCED OFF THE PAVEMENT AND HIT THE BOTTOM OF THE TRUCK, WHICH CAUSED THE BOTTOM PRODUCT LINE TO RUPTURE AND ALSO DESTROYED THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE.  WITH THIS AMOUNT OF DAMAGE ALL THAT COULD BE DONE WAS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL (SORBENT PADS & BOOMS, BUCKETS & TRASH BARRELS) UNTIL ANOTHER TRUCK ARRIVED TO PUMP OUT THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  TO PREVENT A SIMILAR  INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE STEPS ARE BEING TAKEN TO FABRICATE SOME KIND OF GUARD TO KEEP THE DRIVE SHAFT FROM STRIKING ANY CRITICAL COMPONENTS IF IT FAILS.

column168: THE TANKS' VENT CAP ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT WHICH FORMED A VAPOR INSIDE THE TRAILER. ALL PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN INCLUDING CALLING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HEPACO (ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY).  THERE WAS NO DANGER TO THE PUBLIC OR THE ENVIRONMENT SO HEPACO UNLOADED THE TANK AND THE CONSIGNEE SENT THEIR TRUCK IN TO PICK IT UP AND PRODUCT, AS WELL AS CARDBOARD WERE IN NEED OF DISPOSAL AND HEPACO WAS TAKING CONTROL OF THIS, BY DISPOSING IT. THE CONSIGNEE AND HEPACO CONFIRMED THAT THE VENT CAP/VALVE WAS BAD OR THAT THE TANK HAD BEEN OVERFILLED.

UNIT NOTED LEAKING (CYCLOHEXYLAMINE) WHEN ARRIVED INTO NEW ORLEANS, LA GATE.  CONTACTED EMI.  LOUISANA POLICE AND DEQ WERE NOTIFIED OF LEAK.  UNIT WAS LEAKING BETWEEN CAP AND VALVE WHICH WAS DRIPPING OUT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT LEAK CAUSED BY BAD PRIMARY INTERNAL VALVE.  LOUISANA POLICE/DEQ DECIDED UNIT NEEDED TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK.  GULF STATES/BOASSO (OWNER) HANDLED THE COMPLETE REMEDIATION AND TRANSFER OF LIQUID.

TANK CAR WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE (BALTIMORE TRANSFLO TERMINAL AT 1525 ANDRE STREET), AND THE TRANSFLO TERMINAL CONDUCTED A TANK CAR ARRIVAL INSPECTION.  THE INSPECTION REVEALED A SLIGHT CRACK AT THE WELD OF THE TANK CAR BELLY PLATE, AND A VERY SLIGHT SEEPAGE OF PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED, AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO UNLOAD THE TANK CAR. TANK CAR WAS UNLOADED WITHIN 48 HOURS OF DISCOVERY OF THE PROBLEM.  THE SHIPPER CONTACTED THE FRA AND OBTAINED WRITTEN APPROVAL FOR MOVEMENT OF THE TANK CAR TO THE UNION TANK CAR COMPANY IN MARION, OHIO.  PICTURES 1 AND 2 ARE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT, SHOWING THE LOCATION OF THE CRACKS ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TANK CAR.  AS OF THE WRITING OF THIS REPORT, THE RESIDUE TANK CAR HAS NOT BEEN MOVED FROM THE TRANSFLO TERMINAL.  NOTE THAT BLOCK 41 ABOVE IS INDICATED AS "OTHER", AS THE WRITER OF THIS REPORT DOES NOT KNOW WHAT ACTION, IF ANY, CONTRIBUTED TO THE PACKAGING FAILURE.

EMERY ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO A CALL A FOUND A PACKAGE WITH A DAMP STAIN AND SMELLING OF JET - A- FUEL.  THE RESPONSE TEAM PLACED THE WET PACKAGE INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND TAPED IT SHUT.  IT WAS THEN TURNED OVER TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS DEPARTMENT OF DISPOSITION. column168: WHEN TRLR DOOR OPENED @ CONSIGNEE DOCK, STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED AND SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON TOP OF DRUM (APPROX 1/4 INCH).  CONSIGNEE REFUSED TO ACCEPT AND DRIVER WAS TOLD NOT TO LEAVE SITE UNTIL DRUM WAS TAKEN CARE OF. SHIPPER SENT SOME ONE FROM THEIR WATERLOO, IA PLANT TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP OF THE DRUM THEY TOOK POSSESSION @ THE CONSIGNEE'S SITE.

WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE DAMAGED, TWENTY GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY, ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY, THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT DURING LOADING. HAZMAT ONE, OF OLATHE, KS, WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING SIX CARTONS EACH CONTAINING THREE, THREE POUND BAGS OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED RELEASING PRODUCT AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY A HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM ONE OF THE INNER CARTONS. APPARENTLY THE CARTON WAS DAMAGED BY HEAVY TOP FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL "C" PROTECTION, BROOM AND DUSTPAN TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. THE DAMAGED CARTON OF PRODUCT, FREE PRODUCT, PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINING FIVE CARTONS IN THE SHIPMENT WERE UNAFFECTED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED TWO HUNDRED AND SEVENTY FIVE GALLON TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED RELEASING PRODUCT IN THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF PRODUCT RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON THE TOP OF THE TOTE TANK. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES, GOGGLES TYVEK SUITS AND ABSORBENT TOWELS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. THE GLOVES, GOGGLES, TYVEK SUITS AND ABSORBENT TOWELS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE CLOSURE ON THE TOTE TANK WAS TIGHTENED BY THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM. THE TOTE TANK WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A DISCREPANCY IN THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SPILLED EXISTS WITH THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROLS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT WHICH STATES THAT 30-40 GALLONS LOST, AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DELIVERED TO CUSTOMER.  THE MATERIAL WAS METERED WHEN TRANSFERRED TO A NEW CONTAINER AT THE CUSTOMER'S YARD.  A TOTAL OF 3.6 GALS WAS REPORTED MISSING FROM CONTAINER. ON MARCH 21, 2001, A WESTERN FARM SERVICE EMPLOYEE COMPLETED FILLING OF PROWL 3.3 EC INTO 110 GAL RETURNABLE CONTAINERS AND LOADED IT ON 5TH WHEEL TRAILER.  OTHER PRODUCTS ON SAME LOAD WERE, 1000LBS OF THIMET LOCK LOAD, 12.5 GALS FURADAN 4F, 10 GALS DIMETHOIATE, 27.50 GALS MALATHION 8E, AND 2 GALS SPREADER STICKER FOR DELIVERY TO CUSTOMERS IN MOHAVE VALLEY, AZ.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS, THE DRIVER LEFT THE POSTON FACILITY, AND PROCEEDED TO US 95 VIA AGNES WILSON ROAD.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0905 OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPED BY THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL ABOUT 5 MILES SOUTH OF NEEDLES, CA FOR SPILLING PRODUCT.  THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT IS ATTACHED.  WE DISPATCHED ANOTHER EMPLOYEE, WITH A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS(, AS REQUESTED BY THE CHP. NOTIFICATION WAS RECEIVED THAT THE SALES REPRESENTATIVE FOR BASF WAS IN THE AREA, AND WE REQUESTED HE PROCEED TO THE SITE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE.  THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES RESPONDED AS PER CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL REQUEST.  SAN BERNADINO SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT, CALTRANS, BUREAU  OF LAND MANAGEMENT. AND THE SAN BERNADINO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL, US 95 NORTHBOUND LANE WAS CLOSED FROM APPROXIMATELY 1015 TO 1510 HOURS.  THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER, WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND DISPOSED OF BY HAZPAC, INC., 9980 CHERRY AVENUE, FONTANA, CA. 92335 AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE BY THE SAME AGENT. A COPY OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 OUR DRIVER AND THE MATERIAL WAS PERMITTED TO PROCEED TO HIS DELIVERY POINTS.  ONE CHP OFFICER COMPLAINED OF SKIN IRRITATION AND SORE THROAT AND WAS TRANSPORTED VIA AMBULANCE TO THE COLORADO RIVER MEDICAL CENTER, NEEDLES, CA.  HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED.  TO PREVENT THE SAME INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN INSTITUTED TO HAVE EACH LOAD CHECKED BY A SECOND EMPLOYEE TO INSURE THAT THE LOAD IN PROPERLY SECURED AND ALL CAPS.COVER PLATES ARE IN TACT.  THE LOADER AND THE CHECKER WILL EACH SIGN THE DELIVERY TICKET.

WHILE UNLOADING, THREE LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE BUNGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNGS ON THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE DRUMS WERE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ONE ROADWAY EXPRESS INC EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED.

WHILE UNLOADING, FIFTEEN WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING FIFTY-EIGHT JUGS WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZAMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, 15 WET CARTONS AND TWO DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, 50 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE 58 AFFECTED JUGS WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE FREIGHT LOADER AT THE ORIGIN TERMINAL HAD LOADED A PALLET OF FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARTON WHICH WAS LOADED ON THE FLOOR.  THE LOADER DID NOT PROPERLY SECURE THE PALLET OF FREIGHT WITH SUPPORT DUNNAGE. IN TRANSIT THE PALLET OF FREIGHT FELL AND STRUCK THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARTON OF PRODUCT.  DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FREIGHT MUST BE LOADED ON TRAILERS IN A MANNER WHICH WILL PREVENT THE FREIGHT FROM BEING DAMAGED IN TRANSIT.

SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 50 CARTONS SHRINK WRAPPED ON A WOODEN PALLET.  TWO OF THE BOARDS ON THE PALLET WERE BAD AND IN TRANSIT THE BOARDS BROKE WHICH CAUSED SOME OF THE CARTONS TO SHIFT OFF THE PALLET AND FALL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ONE OF THE CARTONS WAS SEVERELY CRUSHED WHICH CRUSHED TWO OF THE CANS CAUSING A LOSS OF PRODUCT INSIDE.  CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  SHIPPERS SHOULD ENSURE THAT PALLETS ARE WORTHY OF TRANSPORTATION BEFORE SHIPPING OUT.

DRIVER SWEPT UP THE SPILLAGE AND DISPOSED OF IT IN THE CONSIGNEE'S (OF THE H/M) SYSTEM AT TIME OF DELIVERY. DRIVER ALSO COMPLAINED THAT HE EXPERIENCED SOME COUGHING AFTER DOING SO. AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE CARRIER'S INSURANCE DEPT.  THE DRIVER WAS OFFERED BUT DECLINED MEDICAL ATTENTION AND REPORTED FOR WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY. LOCAL DRIVER LEFT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ARRIVING AT THE CONSIGNEE TWENTY MINUTES LATER TO MAKE DELIVERY OF A SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT.  WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR HE ENCOUNTERED AN OVERPOWERING ODOR.  THE ODOR BEGAN TO PERMEATE THE DOCK AREA.  CONSIGNEE'S IN-HOUSE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SUMMONED AND IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED. column168: DRIVER WAS DELIVERING GASOLINE TO FREMONT FROM THE AMOCO TERMINAL IN COUNCIL BLUFFS, IA. DRIVER WAS TAKING THE MERGING LANE FROM HIGHWAY 36 ONTO HIGHWAY 275, WHEN TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER. DRIVER CALLED OFFICE AND OFFICE CALLED FIRE DEPARTMENT. FIRE DEPARTMENT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL'S DEPARTMENT DECIDED THAT THE ONLY WAY TO GET THE FUEL OFF THE TRAILER SINCE IT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE WAS TO DRILL HOLES IN THE COMPARTMENTS SO THAT WE COULD SUCK OUT EACH COMPARTMENT. WE DRAINED OUT EACH COMPARTMENT AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE. THEN TWO WRECKERS WERE USED TO UPRIGHT  THE TRUCK & TANKER. WHEN THEY WERE UPRIGHTED, SOME OF THE REMAINING FUEL SPLASHED OUT ONTO THE HIGHWAY. WE FINISHED UNLOADING THE FUEL THROUGH THE MANIFOLD BEFORE WE MOVE THE TANKER AND TRUCK. RISK MANAGEMENT AND AWARENESS PROGRAMS HAVE BEEN INSTITUTED . I ALSO FEEL THAT THIS IS A DANGEROUS INTERSECTION AND THAT A LONGER MERGE LANE MAY BE NEEDED. HOW CAN 10 MILES HOUR TRAFFIC MERGE INTO 60 MILES HOUR TRAFFIC ON A 2 LANE HIGHWAY?

column168: TRUCK WAS EASTBOUND, CLEAR AND DRY WEATHER CONDITIONS.  ON A DOWNHILL GRADE, DRIVER ENGAGED HIS ENGINE BRAKE.  TRUCK BEGAN TO BOUNCE, THEN WEAVE INTO THE OPPOSITE LANE. STATE PATROL, LOCAL LEPC AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WERE MOBILIZED TO EVACUATE THE INJURED DRIVER AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  TRUCK WAS REMOVED AFTER REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF. column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON MARCH 11, 2001, AT APPROXIMATELY 1930 HRS., A MARATHON ASHLAND PETROLEUM LLC (MAPLLC) TRANSPORT DRIVER, DURING A ROUTINE DELIVERY TO THE SPEEDWAY SUPERAMERICA LLC STATION #1100, LOCATED AT 147 HOLMES STREET, FRANKFORT KY 40601, MISCALCULATED THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) CAPACITY, RESULTING IN THE OVERFILL OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE.  THE PRODUCT GRAVITY FED DOWN THE PAVED AREA OF THE STATION AND ENTERED A SANITARY STORM SEWER DRAIN ON-SITE.  LOCAL FIRE OFFICIALS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN ADDING FIRE SUPPRESSION FOAM TO THE STORM SEWER.  THE KENTUCKY EPA AND THE NRC #559221 WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.  THE SPEEDWAY SUPERAMERICA LLC STATION #1100 WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH VEEDER ROOT OR OTHER TYPES OF OVERFILL ALARM DETECTION.  IF THIS TECHNOLOGY HAD BEEN INSTALLED, AN ALARM WOULD HAVE NOTIFIED PERSONNEL OF HIGH LEVELS IN THE UST, AND THE TRANSPORT DRIVER COULD HAVE STOPPED THE FLOW FROM THE TANKER TRUCK.  IN ADDITION, BETTER CALCULATIONS ON UST CAPACITY SHOULD BE CONDUCTED PRIOR TO FILLING.  IF YOU SHOULD HAVE ANY ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS REGARDING THIS ISSUE, PLEASE CONTACT ME AT THE NUMBER LISTED BELOW.

THE CARGO TANK CAME IN TO OUR FACILITY WITH INCOMPATIBLE FITTINGS. WE INSTALLED A FITTING TO ALLOW US TO UNLOAD THE MATERIAL. THE CARGO TANK WAS HOOKED  UP TO UNLOAD TO OUR STORAGE TANK. AS WE OPENED THE VALVES TO UNLOAD THE MATERIAL, WE NOTICED A LEAK THAT VAPORIZED AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALES. THE EMERGENCY ALARM WAS PULLED AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE ORGANIZATION RESPONDED. OUR CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL, SUITED UP AND USED A WATER FOG TO KNOCK DOWN THE VAPORS. ONCE THE INCIDENT WAS MITIGATED, WE REPLACED THE CRIMPED GASKET AND UNLOAD THE CARGO TANK WITH NO PROBLEMS. WE WORKED THE CARRIER TO ENSURE ALL FUTURE CARGO TANKS DELIVERING THIS MATERIAL WILL HAVE COMPATIBLE FITTINGS. WE SINCE HAVE RECEIVED DELIVERY OF THIS MATERIAL AND THE TRUCK HAD THE COMPATIBLE FITTINGS ATTACHED. THE MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

THE VALVE WAS APPARENTLY NOT CLOSED TIGHTLY AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO DRIP THROUGH.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LOOSE.  HE REMOVED THE CAP, REPLACED THE CAP GASKET AS A PRECAUTION AND THEN SECURED THE CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

USPS PRIORITY MAIL SHIPMENT IN TRANSIT VIA AIR, AA 568 SMF-DFW THEN AA1334 DFW-CLE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID IN THE MID-CARGO COMPARTMENT SHORTLY AFTER LOADING ON AA1334 WHILE AT DFW AIRPORT, TERMINAL C, GATE CG. SHIPPER CONTACTED VIA PHONE, SUPPLIED MSDS INFORMATION CONFIRMING SUBSTANCE AND CLEANING PROTOCOL.  FLIGHT DELAY OF 50 MINUTES INCURRED WHILE IDENTIFYING THEN ADDRESSING THE PRODUCT SPILL.  SHIPMENT RETURNED TO USPS AND SHIPPER INFORMED OF DANGEROUS GOODS REGS.

DURING THE OFFLOAD OF SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT#383, RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED A CHECKED BAG THAT WAS OMITTING A STRONG ODOR AND LEAKING.  THE BAG WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND SEGREGATED.  UPON INSPECTION, THE BAG CONTAINED SEVERAL GARDENING TOOLS, GARDEN CHEMICALS, AND GASOLINE POWERED EQUIPMENT.  APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT (ALMOST A FULL CONTAINER) OF FERTI-LOME ROSE SPRAY HAD LEAKED INTO THE BAG, WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY LEFT A SMALL POOL OF MATERIAL ON THE AIRCRAFT BIN FLOOR.  THE MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND THEN DECONTAMINATED WITH A STANDARD CLEANER. THE MATERIALS WERE HELD FOR THE FAA INVESTIGATION AND THEN RELEASED TO THE CUSTOMER.  INTERNAL INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CUSTOMER WAS QUESTIONED DURING CHECKIN (ALBANY, FLIGHT 1371) BY THE CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENT. REPORTS INDICATE THAT THE CUSTOMER WAS NOT TRUTHFUL IN DESCRIBING THE CONTENTS F HER BAG.  AS TO PREVENTION OF FUTURE OCCURRENCES, HOME AND GARDEN CENTERS COULD POST AIR RESTRICTIONS ON THE REVERSE SIDE OF RECEIPTS WITH THE SMALL "NO HAZMAT" SYMBOL.  SIMILAR POSTINGS COULD BE PLACED AT THE ENTRANCE OF AIRPORT PARKING FACILITIES REMINDING CUSTOMERS TO LEAVE HAZMAT IN THEIR CARS.

column168: BAG 07-63-20 WAS TRANSMITTING MIA FROM BOS WITH A FINAL DESTINATION  OF SAL. WHILE IN MIAMI THE BAG WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE. THE BAG WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN MEDICAL SUPPLIES INCLUDING A SPHYGMOMANOMETER. THE SPHYGMOMANOMETER WAS BROKEN AND LEAKED WHAT APPEARED TO BE MERCURY. THE AREA WAS SECURED AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL S.W.S TESTED THE SUBSTANCE AND CONFIRMED TI WAS MERCURY. THE MERCURY WAS CLEANED UP USING A MERCURY SPILL KIT. THE BAG. ITS CONTENTS AND P.P.E WERE ALL PLACED IN A 55 GALLON DRUM. THE DRUM WAS TAKEN TO ROLLS ROYCE STORAGE AREA PENDING FAA INSPECTION. AFTER THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED S.W.S. TESTED THE AREA AND NO MERCURY WAS DETECTED. ESTIMATE $5,000 DOLLARS WORTH OF MEDICAL EQUIPMENT WA CONTAMINATED IN THE BAG. ESTIMATE CLEAN UP FEE FROM EAGLE/S.W.S. TO BE $600.00 DOLLARS.

column168: CONTAINER YMLU279665-2 WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE M/V GULF RIDGE ON MARCH 5,2001. THE UNIT WAS STORED ON THE COLUMBUS STREET TERMINAL CHARLESTON, SC. IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING A FLUID ON MARCH 05,2001. WE WERE SUBSEQUENTLY REQUESTED BY THE  YANG MING LINGS TO ARREND AT THE PREMISES OF THE COLUMBUS STREET TERMINAL. CHARLESTON, SC AND WITNESS INSPECTION AND CLEANUP OF CONTAINER YMLU 279665-2. WE ATTENDED AT THE COLUMBUS STREET TERMINAL, CHARLESTON, SC AT 1600 HOURS, ON MARCH 06,2001. WE MET WITH TURECAMO ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TES) MANAGER, MR. PERRY FANT. AND CARES SAFETY MANAGER, MR. BILL MARQUET, AND DISCUSSED THE SITUATION. MR. MARQUET REPORTED THE UNIT HAD BEEN DISCOVERED LEAKING ON MARCH 05,2001. MR. FANT REPORTED THAT TES HAD BEEN CALLED IN TO CLEAN THE LEAKING RESIDUE AND TO DETERMINE ITS SOURCE. CONTAINER YMLU 279665-2 (20FT) WAS NOTED TO BE SET ATOP THE ASPHALT SURFACE AND STORED IN THE COMMON USER AREA. WE NOTED THE FOLLOWING CONDITIONS: YMLU279665-2 (20FT) MR. FANT REPORTED THE CONTAINER HAD ORIGINALLY BEEN STOWED WITH STEEL DRUMS AND PLASTIC JERRICANS. EMPTY PALLETS HAD BEEN SET UPRIGHT AT THE REAR OF STOW, HOWEVER MR.FANT REPORTED NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS SIGHTED IN THE CONTAINER. WE NOTED THAT THE JERRICANS HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER PRIOR TO OUR ATTENDANCE. THE STEEL DRUMS WERE IN PLACE AND WE NOTED THEY WERE FLOOR LOADED TWO (2) TIERS HIGH AND FOUR (4) ACROSS. WE NOTED THE FOLLOWING MARKS ON THE JERRICANS AND THE DRUMS: CYTEC CYMEL3717 MODIFIED MELAMINE RESIN IN BUTANOL BUTANOL 16% FORMALDEHYDE 0.9 % NET 220 KG TARE 18KG CYTEC C YMEL MD-98 MODIFIED MELAMINE RESIN NET 200 KG TARE 18 KG CYTEC CYMEL UM-15 MODIFIED UREA RESIN  FORMALDEHYDE 0.5 % NET 240  KG TARE 18 KG F-1 ANTI-CRATERING AND LEVELING ADDITIVE 60 OR 20 KG NET ALSO CLASS 3 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID) LABEL AND UN 1866 NOTED ON THE DRUMS CONTAINING CYMEL 3717. WE NOTED THAT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WAS COVERED WITH A PALE, CREAM COLORED, VISCOUS LIQUID. THE LIQUID APPEARED TO BE SPREAD THROUGHOUT THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AND APPEARED TO BE SEEPING ALONG THE REAR OF THE UNIT. TES PERSONNEL HAD PLACE ABSORBENT PADS TO PREVENT THE LIQUID FROM ESCAPING. TES PERSONNEL UTILIZED A HYSTER TO STRIP THE DRUMS FROM THE CONTAINER. TES PERSONNEL ROLLED DRUMS FROM THE 2ND TIER ONTO A WOODEN PALLET AND THE DRUM WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE ADJACENT AREA FOR STORAGE. EACH DRUM WAS VISUALLY CHECKED FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE OR RESIDUE. ALL 2ND TIER DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. THE DRUMS WERE STORED TOGETHER ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE. TES PERSONNEL UTILIZED THE HYSTER FITTED WITH A DRUM HEAD CLAMP TO REMOVE ALL THE 1ST TIER DRUMS. EACH DRUM WAS LIFTED AND EXAMINED FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AND/OR RESIDUE. ALL THE 1ST TIER DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE SOME AMOUNT OF THE PALE LIQUID CLINGING TO THE SIDES AND THE BOTTOM OF EACH DRUM. TES PERSONNEL UTILIZED ABSORBENT CLOTHES TO WIPE AWAY THE RESIDUE. TES PERSONNEL FOUND ONE (1) DRUM AT THE FORWARD END OF THE CO

AT 1325HRS ON 3-12-01, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY FRANK LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE UNION PACIFIC RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, AND ADVISED THAT THE 40TH STREET YARDMASTER HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY FRED BRYANT, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR.  HE ADVISED THAT TANK CAR NATX 37778 WAS OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING WITH PRODUCT ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR, AND THAT PRODUCT WAS NOT THREATENING ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.  UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION FROM THE FRA, THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF MGR LERCH.  MGR LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR AND NOTED PRODUCT ON SIDES OF CAR.  THERE WAS NO POOLING OF PRODUCT DUE TO EVAPORATION UPON CONTACT WITH THE AIR.  SOURCE OF RELEASE WAS FROM A LOOSE LIQUID VALVE WHERE IT THREADS ONTO THE EDUCATION LINE NIPPLE.  THE VALVE WAS LOOSE AND NOT WRENCH TIGHT, THUS CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE VALVE THREADS DUE TO INTERNAL TANK PRESSURE.  MGR LERCH VENTED THE CAR, REMOVED VALVE, APPLIED TEFLON TAPE AROUND EDUCATION NIPPLE THREADS, AND PROPERLY SECURED VALVE TO CAR WHICH STOPPED RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  AFTER SECURING CAR, MGR LERCH RELEASED CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATER WAYS AFFECTED RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.  NOTIFICATIONS:  1000HRS, 3-13-01, CARGILL CORN MILLING, PAT LIGHTHEART, ETHANOL PRODUCT COORDINATOR.

EXTRA TEFLON TAPE WAS USED ON THE THREADS TO MAKE A BETTER SEAL.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

SIROTEK ADVISED RMCC TO MAKE ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS NECESSARY, AS WELL AS MAKING NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC IN REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT.  SIROTEK CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, VAN WATERS & ROGERS, AND CONVERSED WITH JACK DATIN, OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR, WHO ADVISED HE WOULD RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  DATIN INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND DETERMINE THE MANWAY GASKET WAS BROKEN, ACCOUNTING FOR THE LEAK.  HOWEVER, HE DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT GASKET.  JASON POTTS, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO ASSIST DATIN WITH MAKING A NEOPRENE GASKET, WHICH THEY APPLIED TO THE MAN WAY AND CORRECTED THE LEAK.  ALL CHARGES FOR FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL INVOLVEMENT WILL BE DIRECTED TO VAN WATERS & ROGERS, KENT, WA FOR THEIR HANDLING.

5800.1 BEING COMPLETED DUE TO OPERATIONAL ROUTINE OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS ALTERED. AS A PRECAUTION, THE AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO THE GATE AND THE CUSTOMERS BAGGAGE WAS SEARCHED FOR ADDITIONAL FIREWORKS. I HAVE CLAIMED THE FIREWORKS AS UN0337 (1.4S) BUT HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO VERIFY THEIR CLASSIFICATION FROM THE MANUFACTURER. THE PASSENGERS HAD TRANSPORTED FIREWORKS THROUGH SECURITY CHECK POINT WITHOUT DETECTION. ONE ITEM WAS WRAPPED IN NEWSPAPER, THE OTHER WAS A SET OF LONG, APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2- 3 FEET, OF FIREWORKS THAT RESEMBLED GIANT "SPARKLERS". THE LONG ITEM WAS NOTICED ON THE AIRCRAFT BY ONE OF THE FLIGHT ATTENDANTS. IT WAS THEN BROUGHT TO THE ATTENTION OF THE OPS AGENT JOHN NAKAMOTO WHO NOTIFIED STACY STRINGER  ONE OF THE CSS ON DUTY AS WELL AS KELLY BOGGS THE OPS SUPERVISOR, AND HARBOR POLICE. WHEN STACY ASKED THE CUSTOMERS IF THEY HAD ANYTHING ELSE THEY SAID "NO". AT THIS POINT ANOTHER CUSTOMER SAID THAT THEY HAD SOME OTHER ITEMS IN THEIR CARRY ON BAGS. WHEN STACY INSPECTED THEN SHE FOUND ITEMS THAT APPEARED TO BE FIREWORKS. WHEN SHE ASKED THE CUSTOMER HE SAID THEY WERE CANDLES. SHE THOUGHT THAT THEY LOOKED SUSPICIOUS AND DECIDED THAT THEY SHOULD ALL COME OFF THE FLIGHT WITH THE ITEMS. WHEN THE CUSTOMERS WERE ASKED IF THEY HAD ANY CHECKED ITEMS THEY SAID "NO". THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEARED TO DEPART AND PUSHED FROM THE GATE. WHEN THE HARBOR POLICE ASKED FOR IDENTIFICATION FROM THE CUSTOMERS MR. NGUYEN SAID HIS WAS IN HIS BAG IN WITH THE CHECKED LUGGAGE. THE INCONSISTENCY OF THE CUSTOMERS ANSWERS FORCED THE DECISION OF BRINGING THE PLANE BACK TO THE GATE SO THAT THE CUSTOMERS BAGS COULD BE PULLED. WHEN WE ASKED HOW MANY BAGS HE HAD CHECKED HE SAID "ONE" WHEN WE LOOKED AT HIS CLAIM CHECKS HE HAD "TWO'. WHEN WE ASKED MR. NGUYEN FOR A DESCRIPTION OF THE LUGGAGE HE DESCRIBED TWO ENTIRELY DIFFERENT LOOKING BAGS THEN THE ONES THAT MATCHED HIS CLAIM CHECKS. WHEN THE BAGS WERE BROUGHT UP TO THE TOP OF THE JET WAY, THE CUSTOMER EMPTIED THEM IN FRONT OF THE HARBOR POLICE AND TWO GSC TRAINED SWA EMPLOYEES. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE NO OTHER SUSPICIOUS ITEMS IN THE LUGGAGE AND THEY WERE RELEASED TO HIM THE HARBOR POLICE RAN A CHECK ON ALL THE CUSTOMERS. THEY HAD NO OUTSTANDING WARRANTS AND WERE RELEASED. WE WILL HAVE ACCESS TO THE POLICE REPORT, #011228, ON TUESDAY MARCH 13,2001.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 HRS, 22 MARCH 2001 STEVEN HEROUX, AN APRIA PATIENT SERVICE TECHNICIAN, WAS DRIVING AN APRIA TRUCK, 2000 ISUZU FRR, NH 409631, CONTAINING AN HL190 CARGO TANK, SERIAL #413, WESTBOUND ON ROUTE 102 (WEST BROADWAY), APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE EAST OF HWY 93 IN DERRY, NH.  THIS IS A SINGLE LANE ROADWAY IN A RESIDENTIAL AREA.  HEROUX NOTICED THAT THERE SEEMED TO BE MORE VAPOR COMING FROM THE TANK VENT THAN USUAL.  HE PULLED OVER AND PARKED THE TRUCK SO THAT HE COULD INSPECT THE TANK.  HE FOUND WHAT APPEARED TO BE A MALFUNCTIONING VACUUM VALVE ALLOWING PRESSURE TO BUILD AND VENT THROUGH THE ROAD VALVE.  WHILE HE WAS DOING HIS INSPECTION, A DERRY FIRE DEPARTMENT TRUCK PULLED IN BEHIND HIM.  BECAUSE OF THE EXCESSIVE VENTING AND THE FACT THAT IT WAS RAINING AND VERY HUMID THERE WAS A CLOUD OF VAPOR THAT SOON ENGULFED THE TRUCK.  A LIEUTENANT FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INQUIRED INTO WHAT WAS HAPPENING AND IF THE VAPOR WAS NORMAL. HEROUX ADVISED THAT IT WAS NORMAL FOR IT TO VENT BUT THAT AT PRESENT IT WAS A LITTLE EXCESSIVE.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO STAND AWAY FROM THE TRUCK.  THE LIEUTENANT HAD FIRE FIGHTERS (ASSISTED A FEW MINUTES LATER BY THE DERRY PD) STOP TRAFFIC ON THE ROAD AND CALLED THE BATTALION CHIEF.  IN APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES THE BATTALION CHIEF ARRIVED.  HE INSTRUCTED THE LIEUTENANT TO HAVE THE AIR PURITY LEVEL TESTED.  THE TEST FOUND THAT THE PURITY LEVEL WAS WITHIN LIMITS.  ED BRINKMAN, LEAD PATIENT SERVICE TECHNICIAN, ARRIVED FROM THE BRANCH OFFICE.  THE BATTALION CHIEF ALLOWED HIM TO INSPECT THE TANK. BY THIS TIME THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS LIFTING AND THE TANK WAS FOUND TO HAVE 0 PRESSURE.  THE BATTALION CHIEF SAID THAT NEITHER THE TRUCK OR THE SCENE PRESENTED ANY DANGER.  THE ROADWAY WAS REOPENED, HAVING BEEN CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 45 MINUTES.  THE LIEUTENANT TOOK HEROUX AND BRINKMAN'S NAMES AND ADVISED THEM THAT THEY WERE FREE TO LEAVE.  THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN BACK TO THE BRANCH AND THE TANK WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE PENDING COMPLETION OF REPAIR AND TESTING.
NOZZLE STRUCK OBSTACLE WHILE DRIVER WAS WINDING DELIVERY HOSE UP.

DURING THE UPLOAD OF SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT #1273, RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED A CHECKED BAG THAT WAS OMITTING A STRONG "ACETONE LIKE ODOR". THE BAG HAD ORIGINATED IN TULSA, OK (TUL) AND WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA (LAX).  THE BAG WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND SEGREGATED.  UPON INSPECTION, THE BAG CONTAINED A SINGLE UNLABELED CONTAINER OF A CHEMICAL THAT WAS SUSPECTED TO BE FLAMMABLE.  THE CUSTOMER WAS QUESTIONED REGARDING THE CONTENTS OF HIS BAGGAGE, AND DUE TO LANGUAGE BARRIERS AND THE FACT THAT THE CONTAINER (METAL CAN) WAS NOT ADEQUATELY MARKED, THE TECHNICAL NAME IS STILL YET TO BE DETERMINED. THROUGH A TRANSLATOR, THE CUSTOMER INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL IS "ACRYLIC".  THE MATERIAL AND THE BAG WERE TAKEN TO THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE AND THE CUSTOMER WAS ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD NOT BE ALLOWED TO TRAVEL WITH THEIR BAGGAGE AND WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO TRANSPORT THE CHEMICAL. THE PHOENIX CIVIL AVIATION FIELD OFFICE WAS THEN NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE RED BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D. RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. LITMUS TEST READ PH BALANCE 1. RESPONSE SHEET AD RESULT OF LITMUS HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD ME USE CLAY ABSORBENT TO ABSORB ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRY, AND THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. A TIGHTER CAP COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING ITEM WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: PAT STUDENT, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED FRED BRYANT, FRA HAZMAT AGENT, HAD ADVISED HIM THAT AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PHOSPHORIC ACID HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM TANKCAR UTLX 12158.  MR. STUDENT HAD MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY NOTIFIED.  AN INVESTIGATION BY UNION PACIFIC'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ROCKY MOUNTAIN CATASTROPHE, REVEALED THAT LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS RELEASED FROM A LOOSE MANWAY COVER ON THE TANKCAR.  PERSONNEL FROM RMCAT TIGHTENED FOUR LOOSE MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  EACH OF THE SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE MORE THAN ONE FULL TURN.  AFTER CONVERSING WITH RMCAT PERSONNEL, MR. REIMERS RELEASED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON MARCH 29, 2001 CHEVI SHARMA, AN ASHLAND CHEMICAL EMPLOYEE, NOTIFIED RMCC AT UNION PACIFIC OF A RAILCAR AT THEIR FACILITY THAT WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT OUT OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP.  TANK CAR ACFX 79902 HAD BEEN SET INTO THE FACILITY APPROXIMATELY 36 HOURS EARLIER AND WAS NOT LEAKING AT THAT TIME.  WHEN ASHLAND EMPLOYEES NOTICED IT LEAKING THEY PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE AND BEGAN UNLOADING THE CAR.  LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT LEAKED AND WAS CAUGHT IN THE BUCKET.  A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN BY ASHLAND TO CHECK THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THEY REPLACED THE GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ERNIE SIROTEK, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS ADVISED BY MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS THAT TANKCAR NATX 78121 WAS HISSING.  THE TANKCAR WAS BEING SET OUT FOR REPAIRS. IT WAS DISCOVERED THERE WAS A BROKEN MANWAY GASKET CAUSING A VAPOR RELEASE. THE PRESSURE WAS BLED OFF STOPPING THE LEAK.  MITCH DUGGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANGER, WAS EN ROUTE FROM COLTON CA WITH A NEW GASKET AND TO ASSIST IN REPAIRS.  MGR. JOHNSON REMAINED ON SCENE UNTIL THE GASKET ARRIVED.  THE TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED WITH A TEMPORARY GASKET AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, LINDA SALINAS, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE TEMPORARY GASKET SHOULD BE REPLACED.  ALSO, THE VAPOR LINE HANDLE WAS BROKEN AND WAS REMOVED.  THE CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 1545 PM PST.

column168: MVD ATTEMPTING TO ENTER S/S STRUCK A POLLARD THAT AT ONE TIME GUARDED A FIRE HYDRANT. THE POLLARD BROKE THE #6 DROP TUBE AT THE SIGHT GLASS FLANGE CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT IN THE TUBE TO BE RELEASED TO THE PAVEMENT, THE TUBE INTEGRITY OF THE #6 COMPARTMENT WAS NOT COMPROMISED. THE MVD CONTAINED THE PRODUCT WITH HIS SPILL KIT AND CALLED N.Y.C. FIRE DEPT.
